 or investor update emails, an existing investor typically offers Ramp a te=
rm sheet at roughly double the previous valuation. Because Ramp hasn=E2=80=
=99t burned a lot of money, it never needs to raise, so it seemingly only d=
oes so when both sides agree that it=E2=80=99s worth about double what it w=
as in the last round.
So how=E2=80=99d Keith square a double with the worsening market conditions=
?=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CIt was the easiest decision ever. The traditional Founders Fund st=
rategy is to double, triple, and quadruple down into our best companies,=E2=
=80=9D he explained. =E2=80=9CRamp is the quintessential example of the kin=
d of company we want to quadruple down in.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=C2=A0
Plus, he told me, venture capital thinks on longer time horizons =E2=80=93 =
8-12 years for a venture fund, 3-5 years for a growth fund =E2=80=93 and he=
 views Ramp as a great opportunity to invest over the long term. On that ti=
me horizon, what matters most are velocity and trajectory:=C2=A0=C2=A0
Ramp=E2=80=99s product velocity, which was =E2=80=9Cabsolutely unprecedente=
d=E2=80=9D in his 21 years. We=E2=80=99ll come back to this.=C2=A0
Ramp=E2=80=99s unprecedented growth trajectory.=C2=A0
Paying 80-100x revenues in this market after calling the top seems crazy. A=
nd ceteris paribus it would be. But companies aren=E2=80=99t snapshots in t=
ime; they have motion. Logan Bartlett [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJx=
FkE2OwyAMhU9TlhFxyN-CxWx6DUTAk6ImEIEznfT04zSLkRCWscx773OWcE750FsqJM7L0LGhjv=
gqCxJhFnvBbILXdQdD06pReK18PbSDCMV8Z8TVhkVT3lFs-7QEZymk-NmQElrx0H1nlW9cW7t6U=
lI51QFwyw_gxg7x0rW7DxgdavzBfKSIYtEPoq3cmq8b3PnQK5yOKpdW7pY02zjZTKdPETRIANlA=
XUPbgqygkqPsZTMpBMXy3lbDryzv9-BuSq4zVGWfCln3PP8TWcdEU8ohzjx-PuyKy2fAmQzXdY-=
BDoPRTgv6Ky5d1D4AzIwRM9P0xhKzUv3Q9U3Tc73iMY-W_ah-7AQr-8Rb8V_0DwjHhHk], who=
=E2=80=99s invested in each of the past three rounds at Redpoint, explained=
:=C2=A0
If you pick any trailing point in time, paying high multiples looks stupid.=
 But companies are theoretically worth the discounted sum of future cashflo=
ws. The disconnect is that future growth is always hard to grok.=C2=A0
Let=E2=80=99s grok it.=C2=A0
Ramp=E2=80=99s Unprecedented Growth and How to Value It
In the last Ramp piece I wrote, I included a section titled =E2=80=9CHas Ve=
nture Capital Lost Its Mind?=E2=80=9D=C2=A0 The pace of funding was so fast=
, the numbers were so high, and the double-rounds were so uncommon that it =
was worth asking.
Unsurprisingly, I didn=E2=80=99t believe that Ramp=E2=80=99s rounds were a =
sign of VC madness. Something else was at play: growth.=C2=A0
For many reasons=C2=A0 =E2=80=93 better primitives, examples, funding, tale=
nt =E2=80=93 companies are growing faster now than they were a decade ago. =
At the time, Logan guessed that just a decade ago, it would have taken seve=
n or eight years for even a great company to build what Ramp did in two. Th=
at has implications on valuation.=C2=A0
To highlight how important growth is, I made up an example involving two co=
mpanies =E2=80=93 Company A and Company B =E2=80=93 which each start with $=
10 million in Annual Recurring Revenue (ARR) after a year and grow to $100 =
million in ARR. Company A takes four years to get there and Company B takes=
 three years. That seems like a minor difference =E2=80=93 they both got to=
 $100 million in ARR so fast! =E2=80=93 but it=E2=80=99s actually huge. Com=
pany A is growing at an impressive 115% per year. Company B is growing at 2=
16%! As time goes on, the difference gets dramatic: by each company=E2=80=
=99s fifth year, Company A is doing $215 million in revenue; Company B is d=
oing $1 billion!
I thought that was pretty stark. Those were some unbelievable numbers. 216%=
 growth!? $100 million ARR in three years?!=C2=A0
Whoops=E2=80=A6=C2=A0
I dramatically undershot what Ramp would do.=C2=A0
Ramp launched its product in February 2020. By February 2021, its run rate =
was around $12 million. And before the company celebrated its 3 year birthd=
ay from incorporation, it crossed a $100 million revenue run rate.=C2=A0
That is absurd. In 2019, Bessemer plotted how long it took the fastest-grow=
ing SaaS companies ever to reach $100 million in ARR. Ramp just broke Slack=
=E2=80=99s record by hitting a $100 million revenue run rate in two years f=
rom the product=E2=80=99s launch (it=E2=80=99s not technically recurring bu=
t it=E2=80=99s close enough).=C2=A0=C2=A0
As a once-suffering Slack bull, I understand that early growth doesn=E2=80=
=99t necessarily translate to hundreds of billions of dollars in market cap=
, but Ramp has some things going for it.=C2=A0
First, to go back to our earlier hypothetical, that=E2=80=99s a 734% annual=
 growth rate. That means that by year five, at the same rate, Ramp would be=
 doing $6.9 billion in revenue.
To learn how Ramp grows, whether it can keep it up, how it designs its team=
s for speed, how it can use transactions as mini-apps, and more=E2=80=A6=20
Ramp Fireside with Eric and Karim
The written story is one thing, hearing from Eric and Karim directly is ano=
ther. Next Monday, March 28th, I=E2=80=99ll be hosting a fireside with Eric=
 and Karim live from Ramp=E2=80=99s office in NYC. I=E2=80=99ll ask them ab=
out their vision for the future of finance, how they=E2=80=99re building to=
 deliver on it, and why it=E2=80=99s shifted focus from features to outcome=
s. You can ask your own questions, too.=C2=A0
